Morocco,JxPomMpnd9w,UgwcsYjvad9UanTkDgl4AaABAg,,@nickjohnson562,"Hi guys, great to see you back on and recovering from the lurgy!!

Michael, you were right to dial back on the 110v trips for the RV, but no need to dial back on your multi plus inverter as that has load share.

Your fridge’s coil that makes things cool is about 800w (ish), so that in 110v is a 7.2a draw and 3.47a as 230v. Now if you had your water heater on too (which I’m guessing is 2000w plus), there’s no surprise you tripped out a 6a supply. So I’d say the fridge is probably the only thing you’ll be able to run on such a low supply. As your voltage converter is direct to the grid only, you won’t lose the ability to benefit from the Multi-plus, but it will limit the use of the RV’s original kit.
Your Multi Plus however will guess you’ve got a low supply and steal power from your battery bank when you exceed 6a, but obviously you don’t want to be exceeding it all the time, as you’ll kill the batteries over time. If however Fern needs her hairdryer for a short burst, that’s ok as once she’s finished, the Multi Plus reverts back to charge mode and recover the power-share you’ve just done (plus the solar will still be chucking in juice). I think from memory setting it to 6a will only stop you using it up to 6a draw, also you need to keep 3a back for the Transformer and fridge don’t forget, as the multi-plus can’t see that demand.👍🏻",2026-01-19T22:08:15Z,2026-01-19T22:08:15Z,3,False,1.0,2026-05-13T02:00:58.633322
